## Engineering Standards

**Modern C++:** SKSE development using CommonLibSSE relies heavily on C++20/C++23. Use `constexpr`, `std::span`, concepts, and smart pointers where appropriate. Avoid raw `new/delete`.

**Memory Safety vs Engine Allocators:** The game has its own memory allocators (`RE::MemoryManager`). If you are passing an object back to the engine to own, you *must* use the engine's allocator (`TES_HEAP_REDEFINE_NEW()`), not the standard Windows heap.

**Performance:** The main game loop runs at 60+ FPS. Any hook on a hot path (like `Update()` or `Render()`) must be extremely fast. No heavy string manipulations or disk I/O on the main thread.

**Reversing Cleanliness:** Name your pointers clearly. `unk08`, `unk10` are fine during discovery, but refactor them to `flags`, `actorState`, etc., once their purpose is known.

---

## Context Window Management

**Optimize:** CommonLibSSE contains thousands of files. **Do not** read entire class headers if you only need one method. Grep for the method signature. Use subagents if you need to trace a deeply nested inheritance tree (e.g., `TESObjectWEAP` -> `TESBoundObject` -> `TESObject` -> `TESForm` -> `BaseFormComponent`).

